Hi friends =F0=9F=91=8B,
Happy Friday and welcome to our 19th Weekly Dose of Optimism. Once again: g=
o Phils.
The Weekly Dose is brought to you by=E2=80=A6 Composer [ https://substack.c=
om/redirect/7078ae51-424d-4156-a78e-215b92834bce?r=3D9p0gt ]
Luck isn=E2=80=99t an investment strategy. If you=E2=80=99ve read Not Borin=
g for a while, you=E2=80=99re familiar with Composer [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/7078ae51-424d-4156-a78e-215b92834bce?r=3D9p0gt ] =E2=80=94 the in=
vestment app that let=E2=80=99s you easily build sophisticated trading stra=
tegies. Since founding its algorithmic trading platform in 2020, Composer h=
as helped over 20,000 customers trade=C2=A0100s of millions of dollars. I=
=E2=80=99m one of them =E2=80=94 after finally admitting I=E2=80=99m a terr=
ible trader, I=E2=80=99ve moved my public markets investing to Composer=E2=
=80=99s automated strategies.
Composer has synthesized all of this data, sifting through what works (and,=
 importantly, what=C2=A0doesn=E2=80=99t) to create its most powerful invest=
ing solution yet:=C2=A0Opus [ https://substack.com/redirect/7078ae51-424d-4=
156-a78e-215b92834bce?r=3D9p0gt ]. Put simply, Opus is a quantitative tool =
built on Composer=E2=80=99s vast pool of data with just one goal in mind: m=
aximize risk-adjusted returns.=C2=A0Opus by Composer=C2=A0can help you, as =
a retail investor, close the gap.=20
It=E2=80=99s easy to get started.=C2=A0Just choose your volatility level an=
d start investing in Opus.
(1) AlphaFold=E2=80=99s new rival? Meta AI predicts shape of 600 million pr=
oteins [ https://substack.com/redirect/650b030b-ac4f-4f45-a00a-c578071c88be=
?r=3D9p0gt ]
Ewen Callaway [ https://substack.com/redirect/53b727c1-1cd6-43d9-a2b1-9882d=
792f961?r=3D9p0gt ] for Nature
Researchers at Meta (formerly Facebook, headquartered in Menlo Park, Califo=
rnia) have used artificial intelligence (AI) to predict the structures of s=
ome 600 million proteins from bacteria, viruses and other microbes that hav=
en=E2=80=99t been characterized.
It=E2=80=99s been a tough few weeks (months? quarters? years?) for Meta. Ne=
gative headlines, whistleblowing, stock volatility =E2=80=94 you name it. S=
o it can be easy to forget that the social media giant is also one of the w=
orld=E2=80=99s largest long-term investors in AI research. Sure, most of th=
at AI will be used to fine tune Reels recommendations or target ads or make=
 the Metaverse more performant =E2=80=94 but the underlying research can al=
so be applied to deep scientific research.=20
Zuck has been one of the larger patrons of science over the last decade and=
 his foundation, The Chan Zuckerberg Initiative, has the goal of =E2=80=9Cm=
anaging all diseases=E2=80=9D by the end of the 21st century. To do so, the=
y=E2=80=99ll inevitably need major advancements in how we understand the bo=
dy at the molecular level. AI can be really useful here.=20
Meta=E2=80=99s model predicts the shape of ~600 million proteins, nearly th=
ree times as many as the ~220 million protein structures DeepMind unveiled =
earlier this year. The delta was driven by Meta=E2=80=99s model identifying=
 proteins from bacteria, viruses, and other microbes that hadn=E2=80=99t ye=
t been characterized. While Meta=E2=80=99s model is not at as accurate as D=
eepMind=E2=80=99s, it=E2=80=99s about 60x faster, which enables it to run o=
n much larger databases. =E2=80=9CMove fast and break things with stable in=
frastructure.=E2=80=9D =20
This is the type of Big Tech competition we can get behind.
(2) Why America Must Develop Space, and How We=E2=80=99ll Do It [ https://s=
ubstack.com/redirect/ad7c9638-bd88-45cc-ab2c-915c7217dd59?r=3D9p0gt ]
Ryan McEntush [ https://substack.com/redirect/1a06c1ec-6410-4960-8e87-9fbfc=
fc0ab0f?r=3D9p0gt ] for a16z.com
Space is far too important to simply cede development to others. Control of=
 this new sea and development of the space industrial base are paramount to=
ward the continued strength of the United States, and the prolonging of a w=
orld of free markets and liberal democracies. At the end of the day, this s=
eismic effort requires the might of a strong, skillful, and, most of all, d=
etermined population. As a nation, we can accomplish this task ahead of us.=
 That one small step might spawn another, then cast us forward into a strid=
e =E2=80=94 expanding our civilization into the pantheon of the heavens.
a16z (where I=E2=80=99m an advisor on the Crypto team) is making a big push=
 into space as part of its American Dynamism practice. At Not Boring, we pa=
rtnered with Payload Space [ https://substack.com/redirect/cfd836bc-5c08-4b=
b8-8e34-0b5a82658a7d?r=3D9p0gt ] to publish a full breakdown of The Space E=
conomy [ https://substack.com/redirect/39ba984d-0e47-4292-9cc8-6fd3f6898bf8=
?r=3D9p0gt ] which chronicles the development of the space industry, analyz=
es its value chain, and highlights some of the major players in the ecosyst=
em. Our analysis put a spotlight on growing competition between the U.S. an=
d the Sino-Russian space alliance, but this piece goes a few important step=
s further. It plants a flag in the investment world that:
Space is an important battleground of the New Cold War,=20
We need public, private, and public-private investment into space to compet=
e on that battleground, and=20
Now is a good time to invest in that future.=20
a16z has a history of publishing these paradigm shifting pieces, including:=
 Why Software is Eating the World [ https://substack.com/redirect/276d4bbd-=
4a24-4101-b5cb-4a66029bc2c4?r=3D9p0gt ] (2011), Why Bitcoin Matters [ https=
://substack.com/redirect/e10dd75b-bac3-4226-a31e-fbaddb21a036?r=3D9p0gt ] (=
2014), It=E2=80=99s Time to Build [ https://substack.com/redirect/2cc2fa20-=
eaa8-44b4-99f2-3fdc099d3050?r=3D9p0gt ] (2020), Building American Dynamism =
[ https://substack.com/redirect/e14cc7cd-e187-4f0b-818e-41eb03cea6c8?r=3D9p=
0gt ] (2022). If the aftermath of those pieces is any indication, IT=E2=80=
=99S TIME TO INVEST IN SPACE.
(3) Nuclear energy: past, present and future [ https://substack.com/redirec=
t/9201f988-c80f-4091-ae59-59ea833b3e65?r=3D9p0gt ]
By Julia DeWahl [ https://substack.com/redirect/c9dacce4-f94a-4d4c-84c1-430=
6108befc3?r=3D9p0gt ]=20
Despite these challenges, nuclear energy=E2=80=99s carbon-free, 24/7 qualit=
ies make it undeniably attractive to meet the demands of clean, firm power,=
 where both fossil fuels and renewables fall short. There have been a numbe=
r of promising developments for nuclear energy this year and the =E2=80=98w=
hy now=E2=80=99 for nuclear is strong.
This nuclear energy deep dive from Julia DeWahl [ https://substack.com/redi=
rect/c2344d09-a3c0-42e7-b27b-f81a913ab274?r=3D9p0gt ] is the most digestibl=
e breakdown of nuclear energy=E2=80=99s past, present, and future we=E2=80=
=99ve come across.
Past: It=E2=80=99s actually quite frustrating to see how flimsy the anti-nu=
clear argument is. Flimsy in that the anti-nuclear movement gained momentum=
 due to some combination of poor word association, over-blown media reactio=
ns (exactly zero (0) people died at Three Mile Island), and NIMBYism. Frust=
rating in that the nuclear stigma prevented ~50 years of the world fully us=
ing and innovating on a high-potential clean energy source.
Present: The U.S. relies on nuclear more than you=E2=80=99d imagine =E2=80=
=94 over 20% of the electricity and over 50% of carbon-free electricity we =
use comes from nuclear. The case for nuclear can be made in three points: i=
t=E2=80=99s clean, safe, and efficient. But nuclear also faces some challen=
ges, namely: regulation, pervasive stigma, and rising infrastructure costs.
Future: We need to both combat climate change and generate more energy; nuc=
lear is well-positioned to establish itself as a long-term smart choice for=
 clean energy. It=E2=80=99ll need to overcome some regulatory issues, conti=
nue its PR campaign, and decrease costs (small modular reactors, which we m=
entioned here [ https://substack.com/redirect/95da1450-37ab-4d7b-a3fd-40357=
1b40972?r=3D9p0gt ], are making headway on this front).=20
Abundant clean, cheap energy is one of the biggest unlocks available to hum=
anity. We want all the solar, wind, geothermal, hydro, and nuclear we can g=
et our hands on.
(4) After promising trial results for maternal RSV vaccine, Pfizer says it =
will seek FDA approval this year [ https://substack.com/redirect/45ba1f4b-2=
369-49b3-aff3-48ceadf10609?r=3D9p0gt ]
Brenda Goodman [ https://substack.com/redirect/d4d7af1b-bf16-441d-b013-e29e=
ecf33e98?r=3D9p0gt ] for CNN
=E2=80=9CThe [study data monitoring committee] recommended, based on the da=
ta that we have, that we should go ahead and file, that this offers the pot=
ential for a safe and effective vaccine that could really dramatically help=
 to prevent RSV during the winter season,=E2=80=9D Dr. William Gruber, Pfiz=
er=E2=80=99s senior vice president of vaccine clinical research and develop=
ment, told CNN.
This one hits close to home. Dev just got over RSV. Maya has it. Pretty muc=
h everyone we know with kids is going through the same thing right now. And=
 we=E2=80=99re not alone, there is a surge in RSV [ https://substack.com/re=
direct/1a87de82-e300-4bda-8670-d839022aad56?r=3D9p0gt ] cases in the US.
So the news that Pfizer=E2=80=99s RSV vaccine trials were successful enough=
 to prompt the company to apply to for FDA approval is more than welcomed. =
The vaccine=E2=80=99s trial results were impressive: reducing serious RSV i=
n a baby=E2=80=99s first 3 months by 80% and reducing the likelihood of a b=
aby needing to see a doctor by 50%. Depending on FDA timelines, the vaccine=
 could be out in the wild before next winter.
(5) CEO Patrick Collison's email to Stripe employees [ https://substack.com=
/redirect/b12efa4e-5220-407e-8448-e3f4d91c6053?r=3D9p0gt ]
Patrick Collison [ https://substack.com/redirect/0b45fff3-ff1c-4961-b982-d5=
127156064a?r=3D9p0gt ] for Stripe
While the changes today are painful, we feel very good about the prospects =
for innovative businesses and about Stripe=E2=80=99s position in the intern=
et economy. The data we see is consistent with this encouraging picture: we=
 signed a remarkable 75% more new customers in Q3 2022 than Q3 2021, our co=
mpetitive win rates are getting even better, our growth rates remain very s=
trong, and on Tuesday we set a new record for total daily transaction volum=
e processed. Our smaller users (many of whom are just =E2=80=9Cbig customer=
s that aren=E2=80=99t yet big=E2=80=9D) are, in aggregate, growing extremel=
y quickly, showing that plenty of technology S curves remain in the early i=
nnings and that our customers remain impressively resilient in the face of =
the broader global challenges.
As we=E2=80=99ve discussed previously [ https://substack.com/redirect/c7d74=
79d-becc-4dc0-a072-9d81da231e71?r=3D9p0gt ], layoffs are never a cause for =
celebration. They suck. Aside from the obvious fact that people getting fir=
ed en masse is not pleasant, much of the ickiness is the result of how comp=
any managers handle the process. Some CEOs handle it like this [ https://su=
bstack.com/redirect/046fd38e-ee8a-421e-a04a-8a926f822e99?r=3D9p0gt ]. Other=
s, like Patrick Collison, handle it with a bit more tact and generosity.
But layoffs can also be positive in the longer-term, for the companies, the=
 people laid off, and the wider ecosystem. Aside from the thoughtful execut=
ive comms and plush exit packages, I think there are two optimistic takes t=
o be harvested from this otherwise gloomy note:
Internet Commerce Growth: Despite massive macroeconomic challenges, Stripe =
grew new customers 75% YoY in Q3 and recently set a record for daily transa=
ction volume. Commerce on the internet breeds opportunity, and that opportu=
nity is still growing quickly.
Schumpeter=E2=80=99s Gale: In addition to one of the more generous severanc=
e packages I=E2=80=99ve ever seen (14 weeks, unpaid PTO, bonuses, accelerat=
ed vesting cliffs, healthcare, career support), all 1,000 of the former emp=
loyees now have Stripe on their resumes (and an alumni.stripe.com email add=
ress). That=E2=80=99s 1,000 ex-Stripes looking to bring their skills, netwo=
rks, and pedigree to the next wave of startups. Some will start new compani=
es, many will join younger startups and bring with them experience in scali=
ng thoughtfully. The Stripes=E2=80=99 surface area will increase.=20
Plus, layoffs are generally just the beginning =E2=80=94 going forward, Str=
ipe will slow down hiring after nearly 4x=E2=80=99ing staff in the last few=
 years. Stripe probably didn=E2=80=99t lay off its 10x engineers, but it wi=
ll be less aggressive in competing for the next batch of them. Without Big =
Tech, Stripe included, aggressively recruiting to fill massive hiring quota=
s, startups may have the opportunity to compete for the very best talent.=20
